# 2. B. 
# This is a distribution from 0.01 to 0.99 of
# Lognormal distribution.
from scipy.stats import lognorm
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1)
s = 0.5
x = np.linspace(lognorm.ppf(0.01, s),
                lognorm.ppf(0.99, s), 100000)
ax.plot(x, lognorm.pdf(x, s),
       'r-', lw=5, alpha=0.6, label='lognorm pdf')
plt.xlabel('$x$')
plt.ylabel('$lognormal pdf(x) with s=0.5$')
# Here is a lognormal graph with s = 0.5
# s will determine the steepness of the peak
# and the position of the peak.
Out[7]:
Text(0, 0.5, '$lognormal pdf(x) with s=0.5$')

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1)
s = 0.5
x = np.linspace(lognorm.ppf(0.01, s),
                lognorm.ppf(0.99, s), 100000)
ax.plot(x, lognorm.pdf(x, s),
       'r-', lw=5, alpha=0.6, label='lognorm scale = 0.5')
s = 0.8
x = np.linspace(lognorm.ppf(0.01, s),
                lognorm.ppf(0.99, s), 100000)
ax.plot(x, lognorm.pdf(x, s),
       'g-', lw=5, alpha=0.6, label='lognorm scale = 0.8')
s = 0.2
x = np.linspace(lognorm.ppf(0.01, s),
                lognorm.ppf(0.99, s), 100000)
ax.plot(x, lognorm.pdf(x, s),
       'b-', lw=5, alpha=0.6, label='lognorm scale = 0.2')
plt.xlabel('$x$')
plt.ylabel('$lognormal pdf with various scales')
fig.legend()
plt.show()

# scales. Larger scales resulted in less steep curves and more leftward
# peaks; whereas smaller scales resulted in more steep curves and more
# rightward peaks.

In [27]:
# 1. E.
# It makes sense with to get non-integer means out of discrete 
# distributions, because first, the range may not have symmetric steps.
# Non-symmetric steps could result in non-integer means.
# Second, the probability may not be 0.5 which the distribution
# may has its peak shifted from the middle. This could also result
# in non-integer means. 
# Non-integer averages do not mean in real situation, the discrete
# values will result in continuous values. It means the tend of the
# discrete values to locate around the calculated average despite it
# is non-integer.
